<div class=3D"wp-block-uagb-advanced-heading uagb-block-e3857730"><h3 class=
=3D"uagb-heading-text"><strong>Examples and Step-by-Step Solutions</strong>=
</h3></div>



<p>When learning a new mathematical concept, it often helps to see actual e=
xamples worked out from start to finish. By looking at step-by-step solutio=
ns, you can understand each part of the process, identify where to plug in =
numbers, and see how the formulas come together in a real situation.</p>



<p>Let=E2=80=99s start with a basic scenario: suppose you have a circle and=
 you know the radius and the angle that forms your sector. The =E2=80=9Crad=
ius=E2=80=9D is the distance from the center of the circle to any point on =
its edge. The =E2=80=9Cangle=E2=80=9D is the measure of how wide the sector=
 is. If you think of the entire circle as having a certain number of =E2=80=
=9Cslices,=E2=80=9D the angle tells you how big one slice is compared to th=
e whole.</p>



<p>To make things even clearer, let=E2=80=99s break down a few simple examp=
les.</p>



<hr class=3D"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity">



<p><strong>Simple Walkthroughs of Finding Area Using Given Angles and Radii=
</strong></p>



<p>Example 1:</p>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>Suppose we have a circle with a radius of 10 cm.</li>



<li>We know the central angle of the sector is 60 degrees.</li>
</ul>



<p>Step-by-step solution:</p>



<ol class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>Recall the formula for the area of a sector (using degrees):<br>Area =
=3D (Angle / 360) =C3=97 =CF=80 =C3=97 (Radius=C2=B2)</li>



<li>Plug in the values:<br>Angle =3D 60 degrees<br>Radius =3D 10 cm</li>



<li>Compute the radius squared:<br>Radius=C2=B2 =3D 10 =C3=97 10 =3D 100 cm=
=C2=B2</li>



<li>Substitute into the formula:<br>Area =3D (60 / 360) =C3=97 =CF=80 =C3=
=97 100</li>



<li>Simplify the fraction 60/360, which is 1/6:<br>Area =3D (1/6) =C3=97 =
=CF=80 =C3=97 100</li>



<li>Multiply 1/6 by 100:<br>(1/6) =C3=97 100 =3D 100/6 =E2=89=88 16.6667</l=
i>



<li>Now multiply by =CF=80 (use =CF=80 =E2=89=88 3.14159):<br>Area =E2=89=
=88 16.6667 =C3=97 3.14159 =E2=89=88 52.3599 cm=C2=B2</li>
</ol>



<p>So, the area of this sector is approximately 52.36 cm=C2=B2.</p>



<p>This example shows that once we know the angle and the radius, it=E2=80=
=99s a matter of plugging them into the formula, doing some basic arithmeti=
c, and arriving at the answer.</p>



<hr class=3D"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity">



<p>Example 2:</p>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>Radius of the circle: 5 cm</li>



<li>Central angle of the sector: 180 degrees (this is half the circle)</li>
</ul>



<p>Step-by-step solution:</p>



<ol class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>Use the same formula:<br>Area =3D (Angle / 360) =C3=97 =CF=80 =C3=97 (R=
adius=C2=B2)</li>



<li>Plug in the values:<br>Angle =3D 180 degrees<br>Radius =3D 5 cm<br>Radi=
us=C2=B2 =3D 5 =C3=97 5 =3D 25 cm=C2=B2</li>



<li>Substitute:<br>Area =3D (180 / 360) =C3=97 =CF=80 =C3=97 25</li>



<li>180/360 simplifies to 1/2:<br>Area =3D (1/2) =C3=97 =CF=80 =C3=97 25</l=
i>



<li>(1/2) =C3=97 25 =3D 12.5<br>Area =3D 12.5 =C3=97 =CF=80</li>



<li>Using =CF=80 =E2=89=88 3.14159:<br>Area =E2=89=88 12.5 =C3=97 3.14159<b=
r>Area =E2=89=88 39.2699 cm=C2=B2</li>
</ol>



<p>Half the circle with a radius of 5 cm has an area of about 39.27 cm=C2=
=B2, which makes sense because half the circle should be half of =CF=80 =C3=
=97 (5=C2=B2) =3D =CF=80 =C3=97 25 =3D 78.54 cm=C2=B2 total, and half of th=
at is about 39.27 cm=C2=B2.</p>



<hr class=3D"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity">



<p><strong>Examples Using Arc Length</strong></p>



<p>Sometimes, you might not be given the central angle directly. Instead, y=
ou might know the arc length, which is the length of the curved portion of =
the sector=E2=80=99s edge. If you know the arc length (let=E2=80=99s call i=
t L) and the radius (R), you can find the area of the sector using a differ=
ent approach.</p>



<p>The relationship here is that the arc length is part of the circumferenc=
e of the entire circle. The full circumference of a circle is 2 =C3=97 =CF=
=80 =C3=97 R. If you know just the arc length, the fraction of the full cir=
cle you have is L / (2 =C3=97 =CF=80 =C3=97 R). You can use this fraction t=
o find the area as well.</p>



<p>Example 3:</p>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>Radius of the circle: 8 cm</li>



<li>Arc length of the sector: 12 cm</li>
</ul>



<p>Step-by-step solution:</p>



<ol class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>Find what fraction of the full circumference the arc length represents:=
<br>Full circumference =3D 2 =C3=97 =CF=80 =C3=97 Radius =3D 2 =C3=97 =CF=
=80 =C3=97 8 =3D 16=CF=80 cm<br>Fraction =3D Arc length / Full circumferenc=
e =3D 12 / (16=CF=80)</li>



<li>Once we know this fraction, we multiply it by the total area of the cir=
cle to get the area of the sector.<br>Total area of the circle =3D =CF=80 =
=C3=97 (Radius=C2=B2) =3D =CF=80 =C3=97 (8=C2=B2) =3D =CF=80 =C3=97 64 =3D =
64=CF=80 cm=C2=B2</li>



<li>Area of the sector =3D Fraction =C3=97 Total area<br>=3D (12 / (16=CF=
=80)) =C3=97 (64=CF=80)</li>



<li>Notice that =CF=80 will cancel out:<br>Area =3D (12 / 16) =C3=97 64 (be=
cause the =CF=80 in the denominator and numerator cancel)</li>



<li>Simplify (12/16) =3D 3/4<br>Area =3D (3/4) =C3=97 64 =3D 48 cm=C2=B2</l=
i>
</ol>



<p>So, using the arc length, we found that the area of the sector is 48 cm=
=C2=B2.</p>



<hr class=3D"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity">



<p>By studying these examples, you can see the logical steps involved in fi=
nding the area of a sector:</p>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>Identify what information you have (angle, radius, arc length).</li>



<li>Choose the appropriate formula.</li>



<li>Carefully plug in the numbers.</li>



<li>Perform the arithmetic step-by-step.</li>



<li>Arrive at a clear, understandable final answer.</li>
</ul>



<p>With practice, these steps will become more natural, and you will be abl=
e to solve problems more quickly and confidently. As you work through more =
examples, feel free to use the calculator provided on the site to double-ch=
