 central angle in radians</li><li>r is still the radius of the circle</li><=
/ul>Which formula you choose depends on how your angle is presented.</li>



<li><strong>Calculate the Area Step-by-Step:</strong><br>Suppose you have a=
 shaded sector with a 90=C2=B0 angle and a circle radius of 10 cm. Using th=
e degree-based formula:Area of the Sector =3D (90=C2=B0 / 360=C2=B0) =C3=97=
 =CF=80 =C3=97 (10 cm)=C2=B2<br>=3D (1/4) =C3=97 =CF=80 =C3=97 100 cm=C2=B2=
<br>=3D 25=CF=80 cm=C2=B2If you approximate =CF=80 as 3.14, this is about 7=
